‎Key Verb and Grammar Concepts:
‎Verb Types:
‎Action Verbs: Describe physical or mental actions (e.g., run, think, analyze).
‎Linking Verbs: Connect the subject to description (e.g., be, seem, feel).
‎Helping Verbs (Auxiliary): Work with main verbs to show tense or possibility (e.g., is, have, should).
‎Key Grammatical Rules:
‎Subject-Verb Agreement: Singular subjects need singular verbs (She walks), plural subjects need plural verbs (They walk).
‎Tense: Verbs change form to show time: past (walked), present (walk), or future (will walk).
‎Sentence Position: In English, the verb typically follows the subject and precedes the object (The dog [S] chased [V] the ball [O]).
‎Verb Forms: Base form (eat), past tense (ate), past participle (eaten), present participle (eating), and -s form (eats).
